40:43.875 --> 40:47.512 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
important not to underestimate
the impact of all this activism.

40:47.545 --> 40:51.082 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's changing the politics, so
that now police officers are in

40:51.115 --> 40:54.319 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
some ways being treated like
other suspects when they're

40:54.352 --> 40:56.621 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
being investigated for crimes.
If there is evidence that

40:56.654 --> 40:59.891 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they're guilty, then now they're
being prosecuted, not all the

40:59.924 --> 41:02.727 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
time, not even most of the time,
but some of the time. And from

41:02.760 --> 41:06.164 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the perspective of activists,
that's progress. JEFFREY BROWN:

41:06.197 --> 41:08.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Paul Butler of the Georgetown
Law Center, thank you very much.

41:08.199 --> 41:13.204 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL BUTLER: It's great to be
here. JUDY WOODRUFF: In this

41:22.080 --> 41:25.983 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
week when we think about food,
we take a look now at the vital

41:26.017 --> 41:29.620 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
role bees play in getting some
of your favorite dishes to the

41:29.654 --> 41:33.758 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
table, and the way commercial
beekeepers in the U.S. are

41:33.791 --> 41:37.128 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
struggling to keep their bees
healthy. Allison Aubrey of

41:37.161 --> 41:40.665 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
National Public Radio has our
report. The story is part of the

41:40.698 --> 41:47.572 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
"NewsHour"'s ongoing
collaboration with NPR. ALLISON

41:47.605 --> 41:52.610 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
AUBREY: It's harvest time at
Adee Honey Farms in Bruce, South

41:55.113 --> 41:59.817 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Dakota. Bret Adee's the third
generation to manage the 80,000

41:59.851 --> 42:03.721 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
hives the Adees have scattered
across five Midwestern states.

42:03.755 --> 42:07.959 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He says beekeeping these days is
much harder than it's ever been.

42:07.992 --> 42:12.263 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BRET ADEE, Adee Honey Farms: In
2010, our bees were just

42:12.296 --> 42:16.534 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
destroyed in a couple of weeks.
Most of our bees died. ALLISON

42:16.567 --> 42:20.772 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
AUBREY: Bret says things really
haven't improved much. BRET

42:20.805 --> 42:23.808 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ADEE: I would to see about twice
to three times as many bees in

42:23.841 --> 42:26.677 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
most of the hives right now. It
will be a real challenge to keep

42:26.711 --> 42:30.415 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
them alive through the winter.
ALLISON AUBREY: The Adees are

42:30.448 --> 42:33.251 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
not alone. According to a
preliminary survey from the U.S.

42:33.284 --> 42:36.988 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Department of Agriculture,
commercial beekeepers lost 42

42:37.021 --> 42:41.926 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
percent of their colonies last
year. Bees are a critical part

42:41.959 --> 42:45.797 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of agriculture. Adee trucks his
bees out to pollinate

42:45.830 --> 42:49.567 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
California's almond groves every
year. And it's not just almonds.

42:49.600 --> 42:53.237 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Bees pollinate everything from
apples to cherries and squash.

42:53.271 --> 42:57.208 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
To figure out what's plaguing
the bees, the Obama

42:57.241 --> 43:01.012 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
administration assembled a task
force last year. Scientists at

43:01.045 --> 43:05.016 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the EPA, USDA and researchers
across the country who have been

43:05.049 --> 43:09.487 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
studying the problem are finding
there are multiple issues. Bees

43:09.520 --> 43:14.058 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have fewer wildflowers to forage
on due to a loss of habitat.

43:14.091 --> 43:17.495 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There's viruses that pests pass
on to the bees. Climate change

43:17.528 --> 43:21.732 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is thought to play a role too.
Another issue is pesticides.

43:21.766 --> 43:24.635 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Some studies suggest that a
class of pesticides known as

43:24.669 --> 43:28.940 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
neonicotinoid, or neonics for
short, are harming the bees.

43:28.973 --> 43:32.910 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
These pesticides are coated onto
the seed of about 80 percent of

43:32.944 --> 43:35.613 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the corn that's grown in the
United States and about half the

43:35.646 --> 43:39.784 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
soybeans too. To get a sense of
that scale, imagine a cornfield

43:39.817 --> 43:43.888 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
like this taking up the entire
state of California. That's how

43:43.921 --> 43:47.658 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
much of this pre-treated seed is
being planted. CHRISTIAN KRUPKE,

43:47.692 --> 43:50.695 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Purdue University: This is what
corn seeds look like after they

43:50.728 --> 43:54.532 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have been treated. ALLISON
AUBREY: The pesticide is put

43:54.565 --> 43:56.534 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
onto the corn before it's ever
planted? CHRISTIAN KRUPKE:

43:56.567 --> 43:58.536 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's right. ALLISON AUBREY:
Christian Krupke is an

43:58.569 --> 44:01.038 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
entomologist at Purdue
University who studies bees. His

44:01.072 --> 44:04.642 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
research shows that
neonicotinoids can harm bees.

44:04.675 --> 44:07.645 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What is a neonicotinoid?
CHRISTIAN KRUPKE: A

44:07.678 --> 44:10.882 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
neonicotinoid is -- as the name
would suggest, it's based on

44:10.915 --> 44:13.718 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
nicotine. They're less toxic to
mammals, which is a big feature

44:13.751 --> 44:17.722 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in their wide adoption. But they
are more toxic to honey bees and

44:17.755 --> 44:21.592 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to other insects. ALLISON
AUBREY: Neonics are a relatively

44:21.626 --> 44:24.662 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
new class of pesticide. They
have been around since the early

44:24.695 --> 44:28.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
1990s. They are easier for
farmers to use than the

44:28.299 --> 44:31.435 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
traditional method of spraying
crops. And according to

44:31.469 --> 44:34.772 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
researchers at Penn State
University, their use has

44:34.805 --> 44:39.644 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
increased more than 11-fold
since 2003. Companies that sell

44:39.677 --> 44:42.313 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
them are making billions of
dollars. CHRISTIAN KRUPKE:

44:42.346 --> 44:46.951 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Virtually all of these large
acre plants are being treated.

44:46.984 --> 44:50.421 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, the level of use is way out
of step with the level of the

44:50.454 --> 44:53.591 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
threat. In most fields, and
where we have worked, we just

44:53.624 --> 44:57.728 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
haven't been able to find levels
of pests that would justify the

44:57.762 --> 45:01.132 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
level of use. ALLISON AUBREY:
Krupke published a study that

45:01.165 --> 45:05.169 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
linked bee deaths with the
pesticide-laden dust that flies

45:05.202 --> 45:08.272 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
up during the planting of the
pre-treated corn seeds.

45:08.306 --> 45:10.975 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHRISTIAN KRUPKE: We collected
some of those bees and analyzed

45:11.008 --> 45:15.212 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
them and found neonicotinoids on
them and in them, so there is an

45:15.246 --> 45:20.718 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
intersection between planting
these crops and killing foraging

45:20.751 --> 45:23.154 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
honey bees. ALLISON AUBREY:
Bayer CropScience is one of the

45:23.187 --> 45:26.090 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
leading manufacturers of
neonicotinoids. Bayer's chief

45:26.123 --> 45:29.327 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
scientist, David Fischer,
acknowledges Krupke's findings,

45:29.360 --> 45:33.464 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but he says Bayer has a seed
lubricant that reduces the dust.

45:33.497 --> 45:37.168 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He says that, outside these
acute exposures, neonicotinoids

45:37.201 --> 45:39.170 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are not harmful to bees. DAVID
FISCHER, Bayer CropScience: We

45:39.203 --> 45:41.572 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have done those studies. And
those studies basically show, if

45:41.606 --> 45:45.743 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you spray the product, it's not
safe for the bees. If you apply

45:45.776 --> 45:48.813 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the product to the soil or as a
seed treatment, the level of

45:48.846 --> 45:52.083 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
residues that gets up into the
plant is in a safe range.

45:52.116 --> 45:57.888 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Christian Krupke
is not convinced. CHRISTIAN

45:57.922 --> 46:00.791 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KRUPKE: We find these pesticides
in the water. Bees drink water.

46:00.825 --> 46:05.363 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Plants use water. We find that
wildflowers that grow near these

46:05.396 --> 46:09.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
areas also have some of these
pesticides in them. You add that

46:09.200 --> 46:13.004 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
up over the course of a season,
and, yes, we do find concerning

46:13.037 --> 46:17.208 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
levels. ALLISON AUBREY: Krupke
says those levels do not kill

46:17.241 --> 46:21.379 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the bees, but may leave them
more vulnerable. Bayer's chief

46:21.412 --> 46:24.682 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
scientist says the major threat
to bees is a mite that punctures

46:24.715 --> 46:27.685 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the honey bees body and feeds on
its blood. It's known as the

46:27.718 --> 46:31.122 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Varroa mite. And a recent report
issued by President Obama's task

46:31.155 --> 46:34.458 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
force also points to the mite as
one issue. DAVID FISCHER: Eighty

46:34.492 --> 46:39.130 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
percent of the problem is Varroa
mites and the viruses and the

46:39.163 --> 46:42.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
diseases those viruses cause.
ALLISON AUBREY: But some

46:42.299 --> 46:45.770 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
beekeepers suspect the increased
use of the newer pesticides is

46:45.803 --> 46:49.273 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
making their bees more
vulnerable to the mite. BRET

46:49.306 --> 46:53.344 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ADEE: For 15 years, we managed
that Varroa mite and kept our

46:53.377 --> 46:58.816 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
losses under 5 to 8 percent. Now
we're losing 50 percent of the

46:58.849 --> 47:02.787 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
bees every year. ALLISON AUBREY:
Pesticide manufacturers,

47:02.820 --> 47:07.992 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
including Bayer and Syngenta
have launched campaigns of their

47:08.025 --> 47:13.698 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
own to boost bee health. Both
companies are planting millions

47:13.731 --> 47:19.970 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of flowers in the U.S. to
increase bee forage. And in

47:20.004 --> 47:25.409 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
2014, Bayer CropScience opened
this $2 million bee care center

47:25.443 --> 47:29.046 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in North Carolina, where they
conduct workshops and tours.

47:29.080 --> 47:32.483 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Environmentalists say these
initiatives are a diversion from

47:32.516 --> 47:35.820 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the real problem, the pesticides
these companies manufacture,

47:35.853 --> 47:39.590 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
something Fischer rejects. DAVID
FISCHER: Bayer has actually been

47:39.623 --> 47:43.427 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in the business of providing
products to beekeepers for more

47:43.461 --> 47:46.263 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
than 20 years. It's not
something that we just started

47:46.297 --> 47:50.067 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
doing. ALLISON AUBREY:
Beekeepers in Europe came out in

47:50.101 --> 47:54.205 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
force a few years ago in support
of the European Union's partial

47:54.238 --> 47:58.442 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ban on the use of some of these
neonics. And here in the U.S.,

47:58.476 --> 48:01.412 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the Environmental Protection
Agency says it will speed up a

48:01.445 --> 48:05.216 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
safety review and likely not
allow any new uses of the

48:05.249 --> 48:08.886 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
pesticide. Environmental groups
are locked in several court

48:08.919 --> 48:12.690 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
battles challenging the EPA over
the registration of these

48:12.723 --> 48:17.161 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
pesticides. Manufacturers
maintain that neonics are vital

48:17.194 --> 48:21.165 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for increasing crop production
and safer than spraying. DAVID

48:21.198 --> 48:24.401 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FISCHER: They're extremely
valuable. They increase crop

48:24.435 --> 48:31.108 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
yields often by 20 percent vs.
the other competitors. So, they

48:31.142 --> 48:37.014 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
contribute billions of dollars
to the ag economy in the United

48:37.047 --> 48:39.483 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
States. CHRISTIAN KRUPKE: That
would be true if these products,

48:39.517 --> 48:42.853 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
these neonicotinoids, were
indispensable to these crops, to

48:42.887 --> 48:46.924 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
agriculture, but they're not.
Some of our own work in corn and

48:46.957 --> 48:49.960 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the work of others in the United
States has shown that it's very

48:49.994 --> 48:56.767 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
difficult to consistently show a
yield benefit. ALLISON AUBREY:

48:56.801 --> 49:01.272 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Lucas Criswell farms close to
2,000 acres of corn, soybeans,

49:01.305 --> 49:03.274 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
wheat and rye in Pennsylvania's
Susquehanna Valley. He has

49:03.307 --> 49:05.342 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
stopped using treated seed
because he found it wasn't only

49:05.376 --> 49:09.280 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
killing the bad pests, but the
pests he needed to ward off the

49:09.313 --> 49:11.982 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
slugs that were eating his
soybean crops. LUCAS CRISWELL,

49:12.016 --> 49:16.720 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Farmer: The soil in our fields
are a huge ecology of different

49:16.754 --> 49:20.558 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
critters and insects. And
they're all there. We need good

49:20.591 --> 49:24.094 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and bad. It takes a balance of
them all, and that's what we

49:24.128 --> 49:27.097 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have seen. ALLISON AUBREY:
Criswell now keeps pests at bay

49:27.131 --> 49:30.267 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in his fields by planting crops
that encourage beneficial

49:30.301 --> 49:34.171 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
insects. The treated seeds cost
more, so this method ends up

49:34.205 --> 49:37.741 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
being cheaper for him. Is it too
soon enough to say whether

49:37.775 --> 49:40.144 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you're getting the same yields?
LUCAS CRISWELL: Is there corn

49:40.177 --> 49:43.781 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
growing on that hill? It grew.
ALLISON AUBREY: It looks like a

49:43.814 --> 49:46.617 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
lot of corn. Earlier this year,
President Obama's task force

49:46.650 --> 49:50.654 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
called for a reevaluation of the
pesticides. And, consistent with

49:50.688 --> 49:54.058 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the president's requirements,
the EPA has expedited its

49:54.091 --> 49:59.096 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
review. I'm Allison Aubrey of
NPR News for the "PBS NewsHour"

50:05.569 --> 50:10.574 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in Bruce, South Dakota. JUDY
WOODRUFF: Tonight, on most of

50:15.012 --> 50:18.649 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
these PBS stations, "American
Experience" presents "The

50:18.682 --> 50:21.852 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Pilgrims," a documentary that
explores the religious

50:21.886 --> 50:25.422 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
motivations of America's
earliest settlers. In this

50:25.456 --> 50:28.859 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
excerpt, we learn about the
first Thanksgiving, a harvest

50:28.893 --> 50:33.163 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
made possible by the generosity
of the native Tisquantum tribe

50:33.197 --> 50:35.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
who joined the celebration.
LINDA COOMBS, Aquinnah Cultural

50:35.666 --> 50:38.602 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Center: They stayed for three
days. They went out and got five

50:38.636 --> 50:44.408 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
deer to add to what the English
were cooking. They played games

50:44.441 --> 50:50.080 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
together. There's like four
little facts of what happened,

50:50.114 --> 50:53.217 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and then the rest of it is fluff
that's been added over the

50:53.250 --> 50:58.956 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
centuries. NARRATOR:
Two-and-a-half centuries later,

50:58.989 --> 51:03.661 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at another American moment of
great trial and suffering, the

51:03.694 --> 51:07.364 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
humble event, all but
disregarded by the Pilgrims

51:07.398 --> 51:10.834 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
themselves, would be recast as
one of the most important and

51:10.868 --> 51:15.873 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
defining moments in American
history. We love the story of

51:18.842 --> 51:24.882 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Thanksgiving, because it's about
alliance and abundance, and

51:24.915 --> 51:31.021 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
envisioning a future where
Native Americans and colonial

